  "A linear transformation is a function T: V -> W between vector spaces that preserves the two fundamental operations: vector addition and scalar multiplication. This algebraic structure-preserving property is the defining characteristic.": "",
  "What does the term 'additivity' mean in the context of linear transformations?": "",
  "The transformation can only be applied to sums": "",
  "The transformation adds a constant to every vector": "",
  "T(u) + T(v) = 0 for all vectors": "",
  "T(u + v) = T(u) + T(v) for all vectors u and v": "",
  "Additivity means that the transformation of a sum equals the sum of the transformations. Formally, T(u + v) = T(u) + T(v) for all vectors u and v in the domain.": "",
  "What does the term 'homogeneity' mean for a linear transformation T?": "",
  "T preserves the dimension of the vector space": "",
  "T(cv) = cT(v) for every scalar c and vector v": "",
  "T maps all vectors to the same output": "",
  "T always produces homogeneous coordinates": "",
  "Homogeneity (also called scalar compatibility) means T(cv) = cT(v) for every scalar c and every vector v. Scaling the input by c results in the output being scaled by the same factor c.": "",
  "What is the 'domain' of a linear transformation T: V -> W?": "",
  "The kernel of T": "",
  "The vector space V from which inputs are taken": "",
  "The vector space W that contains the outputs": "",
  "The set of all scalars used": "",
  "The domain of T: V -> W is the vector space V, which is the set of all possible input vectors. Every vector in V can be mapped through T to produce an output in W.": "",
  "What is the 'codomain' of a linear transformation T: V -> W?": "",
  "The vector space W that contains all possible outputs": "",
  "The vector space V containing the inputs": "",
  "The set of vectors that actually get mapped to": "",
  "The set of eigenvalues of T": "",
  "The codomain of T: V -> W is the vector space W. It is the space in which the outputs live, though not every element of W necessarily appears as an output (that subset is the image or range).": "",
  "What does it mean for a linear transformation to be 'injective' (one-to-one)?": "",
  "The transformation maps onto the entire codomain": "",
  "The domain and codomain have the same dimension": "",
  "Every output has exactly one input mapping to it": "",
  "T(0) = 0": "",
  "A linear transformation is injective if different inputs always produce different outputs, meaning T(u) = T(v) implies u = v. Equivalently, the kernel contains only the zero vector.": "",
  "What does it mean for a linear transformation to be 'surjective' (onto)?": "",
  "Every element in the codomain is the image of at least one element in the domain": "",
  "The kernel is trivial": "",
  "The transformation is invertible": "",
  "The transformation preserves the dimension": "",
  "A surjective linear transformation maps onto the entire codomain, meaning for every w in W there exists at least one v in V such that T(v) = w. The image of T equals W.": "",
  "What is an 'isomorphism' in the context of linear transformations?": "",
